25
00:05:13.180 --> 00:05:25.559
John Ellis: you have some sort of task, and you think, oh wow, AI is this awesome thing, let me see if it can do it. You stick it into whatever your preferred state-of-the-art model is, and then it…

26
00:05:25.800 --> 00:05:32.639
John Ellis: just works at it, and it gives you something back. And usually, this leads to one or two… one of two things, which are both

27
00:05:32.760 --> 00:05:40.629
John Ellis: terrible pitfalls to me, which is that it seems like it does a really good job at one pass, and you go, awesome, my work is done.

28
00:05:40.630 --> 00:05:56.950
John Ellis: And you ship it. And if you follow people on TikTok and social media who claim that they're software engineers, they would make you believe that this is their main workflow, is that they don't check anything, and they just have AI write code for them, and then they ship it.

29
00:05:57.040 --> 00:06:08.239
John Ellis: But maybe you realize the imperfections in this thing, or it's absolutely riddled with imperfections. You asked AI to do something for you, and it did a really bad job of it.

30
00:06:08.240 --> 00:06:17.289
John Ellis: And then you just kind of go, like, okay, well, I don't know how I'm supposed to fix it, and then you give up on the task, because now it's too much work to even do it with AI.

31
00:06:17.290 --> 00:06:28.880
John Ellis: And neither of those outcomes is what we want when we're doing work, and AI is supposed to be accelerating that work, helping us with that work. But they're both kind of very realistic.

32
00:06:28.950 --> 00:06:43.559
John Ellis: naive approaches to using AI. Now, obviously, we've heard a lot today about better ways to use AI, so everybody here probably knows better than taking two of these naive approaches, but still, it remains kind of a common way of interacting with stuff.

33
00:06:44.310 --> 00:06:48.790
John Ellis: So to make it kind of more concrete, here's a very.

34
00:06:48.950 --> 00:07:00.589
John Ellis: realistic research project that I have worked on, and I've been working on for several years because it seemed like a thing that was going to be really obvious for AI to help us with.

35
00:07:00.600 --> 00:07:10.289
John Ellis: And even now, state-of-the-art models don't make this so simple. So the task that we had is that we had children's books. Lots of images.

36
00:07:10.510 --> 00:07:24.260
John Ellis: text pages from children's books, and we wanted to have an AI create reading comprehension questions, but a very particular type of reading comprehension questions that sort of

37
00:07:24.470 --> 00:07:26.630
John Ellis: Have a child better relate.

38
00:07:26.750 --> 00:07:33.469
John Ellis: the content on the page to their life, better understand what's going on. It's called dialogic reading.

39
00:07:33.470 --> 00:07:51.209
John Ellis: And this might seem really simple at first, so if you just go to an AI and you say, like, give me a dialogic reading question for this page, it might be kind of hard to see, but both Claude and GPT will give a question that reads like a question, so you think, okay, awesome.

40
00:07:51.290 --> 00:08:10.620
John Ellis: If you read these a little bit more closely, or you've ever kind of worked with… not that I have, but from what I understand through all of my journey on this project, if you've ever worked with 3-5 year old children, you might read those questions and think, are those quite right for that age range for reading comprehension?

41
00:08:10.620 --> 00:08:19.770
John Ellis: And the answer is no, and it turned out that, when we did this, even though we got questions that kind of seemed very reasonable.

42
00:08:19.770 --> 00:08:31.020
John Ellis: Usually, like, 50% of them were bad, so then we said, okay, well, this is a prompting problem, right? We just haven't explained enough what we mean by a question, and so we went back.

43
00:08:31.230 --> 00:08:39.889
John Ellis: And we tried to give it every sort of guidance we could possibly think of how to make a really good dialogic reading question, and still.

44
00:08:40.030 --> 00:08:59.629
John Ellis: about… we got 80% quality on state-of-the-art models when we tried really, really hard. And there were other problems that we discovered. Like, even when questions were generally good, then they would start to really lack diversity. They were basically all the same question over and over again. So, like, yeah, you made that one good question, now you give it to me constantly, and that's not what I want.

45
00:08:59.670 --> 00:09:19.130
John Ellis: And so, all of this is just to highlight that it's not that AI is bad at all, but that there's a lot that needs to be considered when you're trying to use AI in, like, real production and real research questions, and you, all of you here, have your own expertise and understanding and knowledge about what

46
00:09:19.230 --> 00:09:32.939
John Ellis: actually is good, and if you're the one who can look at those scrapbooks and be like, that's not what I want, how do I need it to be better? And all of that, and that's, where, really, your interaction with AI is going to be the most value.

47
00:09:34.530 --> 00:09:51.729
John Ellis: So I've definitely felt that it feels like this sometimes, that I'm asking AI to do things for me, and it's just giving me a bunch of stuff that's messed up, and I get really mad at it. It gives me citations that don't actually exist, and then I think, oh, now I just gotta go do the literature review.

48
00:09:51.730 --> 00:10:03.729
John Ellis: Or it gives me data analysis results that look right and have all the right statistics, until I realize it's because it hard-coded something, because it knew the answer already, and it didn't actually do any of the work that I wanted it to do.

49
00:10:03.730 --> 00:10:14.359
John Ellis: Or I'm sitting there brainstorming, I think I've got a great idea, and it goes, yeah, that is a genius idea. Then later, I found the paper where somebody already did that, are you telling me it's a good idea?

50
00:10:14.570 --> 00:10:22.100
John Ellis: So, I think there's times where it can feel like this wall is, like, overwhelming, but I think the reality is that

51
00:10:22.760 --> 00:10:28.039
John Ellis: AI is genuinely incredible. I really do believe that, as much as I'm kind of

52
00:10:28.180 --> 00:10:33.470
John Ellis: slandering it, how I made GPT slander itself by making a homage.

53
00:10:33.670 --> 00:10:48.059
John Ellis: But the reality is that it can accelerate your research tremendously when you put in your own expertise and take the care to use it really, really well. And so, it can do all of these things for you.

54
00:10:48.240 --> 00:11:04.100
John Ellis: It can totally accelerate everything you're doing, but you have to anticipate what are the things that are going to go wrong, try to identify them ahead of time, bake in your expertise where it might not know it, and really guide it in the right direction.

55
00:11:05.380 --> 00:11:10.669
John Ellis: And I think that research in particular, is an interesting case for this, because

56
00:11:10.710 --> 00:11:29.129
John Ellis: I just said AI is incredible, and that's true, but AI is, in my opinion, equally as incredible as real research is really difficult and hard. That real research wants things that are difficult for AI to just do without any extra guidance. It wants

57
00:11:29.190 --> 00:11:46.209
John Ellis: absolute correctness and reproducibility, and all of the edge cases to be covered, and novelty, and not a single error, because that will propagate through the pipeline and be catastrophic. And AI isn't really, as we saw, necessarily optimized towards all of those things.

58
00:11:46.210 --> 00:11:51.490
John Ellis: That being said, there's a ton that lives in the middle, and there's a ton of, sort of.

59
00:11:51.710 --> 00:12:07.490
John Ellis: compromise space, I would say, that you could make, where, maybe AI can't do the whole thing for you, but it can do a component, and a big part, sort of, using AI is realizing what is that component that it can do for me, that it can help with, and where is that space

60
00:12:09.770 --> 00:12:20.009
John Ellis: So one more analogy, that I really like, and maybe this will sort of help you frame it, is that, I think AI helps bridge a gap

61
00:12:20.350 --> 00:12:37.070
John Ellis: But if it bridges it, it doesn't fly a cane over it. So, if you have some sort of expertise, and you want to move to some problem space, or solve some issue, or do some task where your expertise is relevant, where you've well defined the problem.

62
00:12:37.510 --> 00:12:43.540
John Ellis: AI might help take you there, build a little bridge over to, like, I needed to write this other thing that I didn't know how to do.

63
00:12:43.610 --> 00:13:03.009
John Ellis: But enough of what I know is relevant to get me there. The issue is if you want AI to fly a plane through you over the ocean, you have this task that you really want to do, and you can't well define it because you don't have the relevant expertise, can't evaluate it, because you wouldn't know what would go wrong.

64
00:13:03.260 --> 00:13:10.740
John Ellis: AI will certainly try, but it'll probably give you something really bad, and then you are left with not knowing how you're supposed to progress.

65
00:13:13.300 --> 00:13:16.790
John Ellis: And so, I think that really this is the…

66
00:13:17.200 --> 00:13:29.709
John Ellis: horror story that you'll hear about repeatedly with AI. I know that I've heard about it tons of times with regards to, for instance, like, programmed websites that then had

67
00:13:29.790 --> 00:13:35.989
John Ellis: terrible security and, like, people's critical data, stuff like that, is that

68
00:13:36.030 --> 00:13:53.099
John Ellis: AI is amazing when it closes a production gap for when you already have the evaluation expertise. So, I very much come from a coding side, so for me, this is always the example where it's like, when I know what a code is supposed to do, and what I want it to do, and I could write it myself.

69
00:13:53.140 --> 00:14:06.070
John Ellis: But I don't want to take the time, so I'll have AI write it, but I can still… I know everything about whether or not it's doing what it's supposed to. Where it's very dangerous is where you wouldn't have any way of knowing if what it did was

70
00:14:06.240 --> 00:14:24.759
John Ellis: accurate, or robust, or anything, and then it just does it for you, and you can't properly evaluate it. And so a lot of those horror stories here live in this bottom section, where somebody just said, like, I don't know, it must work because AI's brilliant, and then can't really figure out

71
00:14:24.940 --> 00:14:26.549
John Ellis: Where it went wrong.

72
00:14:28.340 --> 00:14:42.810
John Ellis: And I think I don't have to tell anybody in this room about the importance of, academic rigor, but I think that the point really to make here is that the failures in AI are gonna be kind of…

73
00:14:42.810 --> 00:14:50.739
John Ellis: different. And I hope to really enumerate all of them so that, you know, you know what to anticipate. But I think that

74
00:14:51.790 --> 00:15:07.840
John Ellis: you know, everyone here is probably used to running evaluations and tests and understanding where your results fail and where they don't, but AI will have ways of failing that I think are less obvious, and that's kind of where it gets a little scary.

75
00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:15.450
John Ellis: One big thing is that I think a lot of times the signal that something is wrong is just not there at all. Like.

76
00:15:15.780 --> 00:15:27.820
John Ellis: again, in my domain, which is, like, usually coding, we are well past the point where AI code will ever have a syntactical error in it, you know what I mean? Or if it does, like, it'll just fix it.

77
00:15:28.010 --> 00:15:38.809
John Ellis: So the problem isn't going to be this, like, error that pits you in the face that the code can't run. The problem is going to be, like, something that it hard-coded on line 27 that actually, like, messes up the whole analysis.

78
00:15:38.880 --> 00:15:48.640
John Ellis: And you maybe wouldn't know what the signs are to know that that's in there, and that the whole thing's wrong. Or, bad AI writing? I mean, it reads great.

79
00:15:48.720 --> 00:16:03.649
John Ellis: Like, it'll sound like it totally knows what it's talking about, or it'll give you citations that don't exist. And so it's not obvious where it's making space, so we have to be a little more methodological in picking apart where it's going to make space.

80
00:16:04.360 --> 00:16:13.860
John Ellis: In this way, it's also inverting the normal cost structure in a way that, for me, felt really frustrating for a while, but I think now I'm used to, where,

81
00:16:14.330 --> 00:16:30.279
John Ellis: you know, I'm very used to, like, I put in all of this hard work to write a really long code, or, like, produce something myself, and then once it's working, I feel really confident in writing it. So then, like, you know, running evaluations and tests and producing, like, thoughts that show the results on top of that.

82
00:16:30.380 --> 00:16:42.559
John Ellis: is a little bit less of the work. You know, like, the hard work was making sure it was all perfect from the get-go. Instead, it gets a little bit inverted with AI. So, like, you can have something really, really fast.

83
00:16:42.630 --> 00:16:54.109
John Ellis: And then all of the hard work comes around checking that it's really good, it's really doing what you want it to do, and so you have to, like, think about where you're putting your time a little bit differently.

84
00:16:55.000 --> 00:17:00.679
John Ellis: And then, of course, AI can explain to you what it's thinking.

85
00:17:00.770 --> 00:17:06.459
John Ellis: And that can be useful, but it also can fall into the same trap. So…

86
00:17:06.490 --> 00:17:25.180
John Ellis: I love to read, like, Claude's thinking process, but a lot of times, Claude's thinking process is, like, the same thing as what it ends up telling me, so you can't necessarily 100% rely on what it thinks it's thinking to arrive at your answer to really arrive at your answer. Sometimes.

87
00:17:25.380 --> 00:17:40.289
John Ellis: that's, like, way baked into, yeah, the model's understanding of things, to the context from forever ago that you kind of didn't realize it's accounting for. And so you can't necessarily just ask it why it's doing the things it's doing. We'll always…

88
00:17:42.680 --> 00:17:47.439
John Ellis: Okay, so before I sort of, enumerate

89
00:17:48.240 --> 00:18:01.899
John Ellis: what, in my mind, are kind of the main things to be looking out for. I want to sort of just call out what I mean by using AI in research, because it can mean a lot of things, and I think really all of these apply. It's sort of

90
00:18:02.210 --> 00:18:15.679
John Ellis: it exists, how to use AI in research kind of exists across the full spectrum of ways that you could do this. So the first thing is that AI might be your information processor. Maybe you're feeding it

91
00:18:16.190 --> 00:18:21.909
John Ellis: You know, 100 documents about something, and you're asking it to synthesize that information.

92
00:18:22.090 --> 00:18:30.490
John Ellis: Or, you're giving it 100 Excel sheets and asking for it to, like, aggregate some information. So it's mostly…

93
00:18:30.610 --> 00:18:34.959
John Ellis: Turning a bulk of stuff into, like, a single output.

94
00:18:35.630 --> 00:18:40.820
John Ellis: Of course, AI can be a writing slash thinking partner. You can use it to help draft.

95
00:18:40.920 --> 00:18:49.659
John Ellis: Write certain things, brainstorm with you, synthesize multiple papers that you are having trouble understanding how they relate to one another.

96
00:18:49.820 --> 00:19:08.279
John Ellis: all of that. Ai is your programmer, so this is my personal mode, but I know it's not everybody's, where, for the most part, what AI is doing is just not putting, you know, Python files for you. You say, hey, I need a file that does this, goes and writes it, it's back with it, or…

97
00:19:08.640 --> 00:19:17.179
John Ellis: you know, whatever, whatever the code… the problem is code-based, and you're sort of just asking for a certain thing in that way. The fourth mode…

98
00:19:17.690 --> 00:19:25.110
John Ellis: This AI is the thing that you're building, so there are cases in which maybe fine-tuning a model is a part of the work.

99
00:19:25.110 --> 00:19:38.140
John Ellis: that you're doing, and I still think the same source of considerations actually, you know, come into play if, like, that is the case. Because even if you fine-tune the model, it doesn't mean you understand absolutely everything about, sort of, the now.

100
00:19:38.680 --> 00:19:45.969
John Ellis: personal black box that you fine-tuned. So the same amount of, like, evaluation and rigor should go into that application as well.

101
00:19:47.500 --> 00:19:48.380
John Ellis: Okay.

102
00:19:48.830 --> 00:19:51.789
John Ellis: So I have tried to define

103
00:19:52.020 --> 00:19:58.330
John Ellis: five major pressure points. Places that I think that

104
00:19:58.720 --> 00:20:04.080
John Ellis: really have to be vigilant about, keep an eye out, places where I think that there might,

105
00:20:04.700 --> 00:20:19.410
John Ellis: be an opportunity for things to not go exactly quite right when you try to use AI in research. But then hopefully, some places where also you might be able to mitigate these from the get-go, know what could go wrong, and then use that to your advantage.

106
00:20:22.540 --> 00:20:23.460
John Ellis: Okay.

107
00:20:23.950 --> 00:20:29.390
John Ellis: So the first one I'm calling the invisible decision.

108
00:20:29.630 --> 00:20:40.259
John Ellis: And this is the problem that I think personally bothers me the most, and that I run into kind of the most, which is that AI will make choices

109
00:20:40.740 --> 00:20:45.990
John Ellis: That you didn't ask for, and it won't tell you that it's making choices.

110
00:20:46.030 --> 00:21:04.439
John Ellis: And this can be across a very broad range of things. If you have a particular mode that you've immediately identified how you want to, use AI in research, one of these modes might resonate with you. Not gonna enumerate all of them, because that would take a lot of time.

111
00:21:04.440 --> 00:21:24.179
John Ellis: But the idea of having an invisible decision problem is that there's times in which you will think that you are fully specifying a problem to AI. You want to use this certain methodology, you want it to write Python code, you want it to take in inputs in this format and give out outputs in this format, and

112
00:21:24.480 --> 00:21:40.729
John Ellis: All of that you've splayed out really well, and yet still, it will decide to use a particular algorithm to make a certain assumption about your data distribution, to whatever it is, and it won't necessarily tell you.

113
00:21:40.840 --> 00:21:42.509
John Ellis: I can,

114
00:21:42.770 --> 00:21:55.110
John Ellis: rant all day about this problem that I have, but I've had repeatedly in AI, so I'll call it out as the one that, I run into all the time. Every time that I ask AI to write

115
00:21:55.400 --> 00:21:58.750
John Ellis: A code to do fine-tuning of a model.

116
00:21:59.410 --> 00:22:12.620
John Ellis: It's getting into the nitty-gritty, but it'll do that gradient descent step, that, like, fixing how it's going to make outputs based on what it's already done. It'll do that based also on the input prompt.

117
00:22:12.760 --> 00:22:22.430
John Ellis: And that's just, like, fundamentally not how you do that, and I don't think I have to say that, but I do have to say that. And it took… the first time this happened.

118
00:22:22.450 --> 00:22:33.780
John Ellis: It took me a really long time, like, a lot of debugging, a lot of, like, loss plots, and, like, looking at the token, like, so much debugging. Because, again, like, there's no error.

119
00:22:33.780 --> 00:22:43.129
John Ellis: The trainings aren't wrong. Actually, the loss plots will come down beautifully, they look totally fine, except that it's a fundamental flaw that I think is obvious.

120
00:22:43.280 --> 00:22:45.559
John Ellis: But that isn't obvious to the AI.

121
00:22:45.690 --> 00:22:53.250
John Ellis: And so these can be really hard to catch. I guess this is why I'm saying I could rant about it, because they really are invisible.

122
00:22:53.850 --> 00:23:01.099
John Ellis: And it takes a lot of expertise sometimes to know when things are going well, and to tease them out.

123
00:23:02.380 --> 00:23:10.900
John Ellis: But the hope is that you can make at least some of those decisions visible to you. So one thing is always just to, like.

124
00:23:11.180 --> 00:23:24.679
John Ellis: ask AI to state its assumptions before executing. I know that I said earlier that asking AI to say what it's gonna do is not always the perfect solution, but make it right a plan. What are the steps? What…

125
00:23:25.070 --> 00:23:44.140
John Ellis: you know, like, what are all the assumptions it's making about things? How does it plan on tackling this? What in its mind is the code doing? Or are the key points it's making in your PowerPoint or your document? And then just look at all of it and sanity check it all first. Just like, well, is that how I would have done anything?

126
00:23:44.870 --> 00:23:49.900
John Ellis: sort of going along with that, but I think sort of separate.

127
00:23:50.280 --> 00:23:53.339
John Ellis: As much as you can, try to write

128
00:23:53.780 --> 00:24:03.940
John Ellis: constraints on choices. Like, if there… now, I know that I said the invisible decision problem is invisible because you can't anticipate what would have happened, but still.

129
00:24:03.940 --> 00:24:16.039
John Ellis: it's a good idea to try to, like, splay out what you do know about a problem as well as you do beforehand. The more information that you can bake in, and the more of your knowledge about how you want this done, you can bake in.

130
00:24:16.140 --> 00:24:19.180
John Ellis: The less it'll have to just kind of freeball it.

131
00:24:19.520 --> 00:24:23.569
John Ellis: And a lot of times, just treat the first pass

132
00:24:23.700 --> 00:24:30.560
John Ellis: as a draft of the decision-making process. So if you can, start with a smaller version of a task.

133
00:24:30.950 --> 00:24:44.519
John Ellis: or, like, a pilot version, or, like, a snippet of something, if you think that there's a lot of opportunity for choices to be made there, that helps a lot. So, if you're just, like, writing a massive code.

134
00:24:44.650 --> 00:24:51.109
John Ellis: maybe AI could give you the whole thing in one go, but maybe you want, like, one specific part, you, like, want to look at that.

135
00:24:51.410 --> 00:25:08.990
John Ellis: Actually. And just check all the decisions that go into that. So you don't have to be meticulous about every single part of everything you do. I think it's about understanding what parts to be meticulous over, and that starts from you understanding what are the decisions that you could make that would mess this whole thing up, and let me try to catch those before they…

136
00:25:11.360 --> 00:25:26.809
John Ellis: A second major one that I think is probably, one of the most, sort of, well understood if you've worked with AI is the plausibility track, which is just that, things will… won't approximately bigger. So we talked about this, that, like.

137
00:25:26.960 --> 00:25:44.329
John Ellis: things will read well, or citations will look well-structured, or the code will run and won't have errors. Like, all of these things happen. And, the way to know if things are actually going wrong, is to really just have to

138
00:25:44.430 --> 00:25:48.319
John Ellis: look at what it's doing, which I know sounds really obvious, but just…

139
00:25:48.990 --> 00:25:55.440
John Ellis: calling it out anyway, because we all know it happens. Really, you can't just blindly trust

140
00:25:55.600 --> 00:26:09.509
John Ellis: AI when it comes to a lot of things, and that it has to be your job to say, well, is there a test case that I know that I can try this out on? And that test case will inform to me if it's really doing what I think

141
00:26:09.510 --> 00:26:27.779
John Ellis: it's doing. Or identify what your edge cases are. So if you give it lots of examples that are super easy, maybe it does a wonderful job on the easy examples, but do you have a case where you know if it doesn't get the edge case, it actually didn't get the methodology really right, and then look at the edge cases.

142
00:26:28.780 --> 00:26:32.450
John Ellis: verified claims independently, so if…

143
00:26:33.870 --> 00:26:44.689
John Ellis: don't make an assumption that because it performs well in one case, or because it performs well in easy cases, that things are necessarily going well. So for me, this

144
00:26:44.990 --> 00:27:00.030
John Ellis: still happens with citations, even when I ask it to, like, go and check the citations. Sometimes, like, 9 of 10 of them are right. You know, I still don't look at every single one of papers that it tells me are relevant to what I'm looking at, because it's just…

145
00:27:01.080 --> 00:27:08.370
John Ellis: It's just that all those things are independent from one another, so you can't necessarily know that because one was right, universally, they're right.

146
00:27:10.950 --> 00:27:20.230
John Ellis: Another sort of big one, is the evaluation gap. This is basically the case where

147
00:27:20.480 --> 00:27:32.879
John Ellis: Sometimes it happens that you want to use AI to do something for you, and you sort of run into this wall where actually you realize that figuring out if the AI did a good job of it is more work than you could have just done living yourself.

148
00:27:32.950 --> 00:27:47.289
John Ellis: Like, AI is maybe formatting some things wrong, and all of a sudden you don't trust the whole batch of those things, and you try to correct it, and, like, it's still not doing it right, and now you think, like, I just gotta do it myself, because now, how do I know what's going on with any of this?

149
00:27:48.750 --> 00:28:01.010
John Ellis: I think that this is an opportunity, and there's lots of opportunities for, stuff like skills and agents to help kind of bridge some of these gaps. I think this is an opportunity there, to sort of

150
00:28:01.250 --> 00:28:09.300
John Ellis: leverage your expertise, and to make sure that your expertise is known to the model as best as you can. So…

151
00:28:09.950 --> 00:28:25.130
John Ellis: Really, it means critically looking at what evaluation means for your project, and can you give that insight that you have about what evaluation means to the model, so that it can understand what sorts of evaluations to run ahead of time?

152
00:28:25.630 --> 00:28:36.829
John Ellis: And so this can be, yeah, like, running… writing skills to run certain test cases. Like, there's well-known tests that have to pass on your data for it to be right, like.

153
00:28:37.320 --> 00:28:48.739
John Ellis: give that to the model so it knows to check these things for you. Sometimes the evaluation gap, I think, can feel enormous, and a lot of the work is in, like, closing it by helping the area understand

154
00:28:48.920 --> 00:28:53.509
John Ellis: what it's supposed to be doing. A lot of this also just happens

155
00:28:53.820 --> 00:29:02.710
John Ellis: when you try to scope ahead of time, so understanding, like, what is the complexity of the problem, can I anticipate some of these errors, or…

156
00:29:02.950 --> 00:29:09.690
John Ellis: places where it'll go wrong, or evaluations that it's gonna have to run, and just tell it to run them from the get-go.

157
00:29:10.220 --> 00:29:28.839
John Ellis: And then, of course, ask yourself if you could just figure it out if you had to, and if you did have to go down that path, like, would this whole thing have been a waste of your time? Is, I think, just an important question to keep in your mind, if, like, AI is meant to make things easier for you, and if it would potentially make things worse for you.

158
00:29:28.950 --> 00:29:31.380
John Ellis: And maybe just let that help go.

159
00:29:33.840 --> 00:29:35.710
John Ellis: Okay.

160
00:29:36.770 --> 00:29:49.770
John Ellis: lots of these potential issues. The next one is the aggregation effect. I think that this one, is also fairly well known, which is just kind of that there can be significant

161
00:29:49.890 --> 00:30:03.810
John Ellis: errors or bias over lots of model outputs. So where a single instance looks okay, you might actually have a really bad systematic issue once you look at a thousand examples of something.

162
00:30:05.040 --> 00:30:11.750
John Ellis: Of course, the easiest thing is always just to check the distribution, check lots of use cases.

163
00:30:12.110 --> 00:30:22.179
John Ellis: Sample strategically, not necessarily randomly, so it goes a little bit back to the point of if you have edge cases, it's always best to understand

164
00:30:22.420 --> 00:30:31.550
John Ellis: Where… to anticipate where there is an opportunity to not be getting the full picture, or the generalized picture, and then try to take that apart from the get-go.

165
00:30:31.570 --> 00:30:43.849
John Ellis: Of course, if you are able to take statistics, look at them over all of your data, if you can, or as much of your data as you can. And then, of course, just ask yourselves, like, what are the biases that are acceptable?

166
00:30:44.030 --> 00:30:55.309
John Ellis: There are real instances where there could be some errors or biases in a pipeline, and that is okay for some reason, as long as they're well known and well characterized.

167
00:30:55.790 --> 00:31:03.030
John Ellis: I have a good example of one of these. So, I looked at the emails that I generated last night that you all just got.

168
00:31:03.160 --> 00:31:12.060
John Ellis: And and it looks fine. And Jesse Bloper was the last person who connected to the person that… let me open another email.

169
00:31:12.390 --> 00:31:14.809
John Ellis: The last person who's connected for this person was

170
00:31:15.150 --> 00:31:32.679
John Ellis: Jesse Bloker. Yeah. And then I opened up a random third one, and guess who was the third person who was listening? Jesse Bloker. So, so it was the Jesse Bloker bias effect that, that didn't appear until I actually looked at a number of them to see that there was indeed a problem with the distribution. Yes.

171
00:31:32.680 --> 00:31:38.439
John Ellis: Definitely, yes. And Jesse Bolt, I'm sure, is a great person to talk to with, not for…

172
00:31:39.060 --> 00:31:41.009
John Ellis: At the same time.

173
00:31:41.580 --> 00:32:01.410
John Ellis: Okay, and then the final, point is, just the cost delusion, which is sort of an aggregate point of all of these others, which is that sometimes you anticipate that AI will save you time, and enough of these issues means that it saves you time. And to the best of your ability.

174
00:32:02.050 --> 00:32:06.889
John Ellis: Anticipating this is nice. Now, it's not always possible. Sometimes it really just

175
00:32:07.020 --> 00:32:20.240
John Ellis: does take more of your time than you realize, and you kind of stick with it, or sometimes, you know, like, the time's just lost. But I try to really ask myself. I'm completely guilty of

176
00:32:20.240 --> 00:32:29.989
John Ellis: using Claude to write all of my emails. I just really don't like writing emails. It really stresses me out. I think I'm, like, obsessed over the wording, so I have Claude write my emails.

177
00:32:29.990 --> 00:32:44.099
John Ellis: Now, I cannot tell you how many times it's taken me an hour to write an email, because I go back and forth with Claude about, like, well, I don't know, are they going to interpret this that way? Like, that sounds like… am I being rude if I said… I could have written the email myself at that point.

178
00:32:44.560 --> 00:32:47.149
John Ellis: So I've learned that buying personal

179
00:32:47.260 --> 00:32:57.530
John Ellis: thing is that I shouldn't use Cloud to write my emails, because my obsessiveness is gonna make that a problem. But there are real cases where it's not your own obsessiveness, it's, you know.

180
00:32:57.590 --> 00:33:13.049
John Ellis: that having to specify 200 things about exactly how the data should look, like, maybe you should have just gone in and, like, edited something, you know what I mean? There's lots of cases where the best thing to do is try a pilot, and if it seems like things are taking too much work.

181
00:33:13.180 --> 00:33:21.659
John Ellis: sometimes it's just that AI would take too much work. Like, you'd have to over-specify, especially if it's, like, a one single instance, like.

182
00:33:21.970 --> 00:33:38.879
John Ellis: there's one thing to put in a lot of work to, like, write a scale or a code that's going to be really reusable to you, but if you're trying to, like, just make one single PowerPoint presentation, and you're spending, like, four days with Claude, editing how the slide looks, like, probably give up on that.

183
00:33:41.420 --> 00:33:42.330
John Ellis: Okay.

184
00:33:42.820 --> 00:33:47.280
John Ellis: So I gave you some potential solutions, but I mostly just enumerated

185
00:33:47.410 --> 00:33:53.880
John Ellis: all of the things that could go wrong. And so I have tried here to develop a

186
00:33:54.160 --> 00:34:12.550
John Ellis: more of a framework of 6 questions, I think, to ask yourself whenever you're beginning using AI on a project, or using AI for a component, to sort of try to preempt some of these issues. You don't have… so you don't have to correct them, you can sort of ask yourself, like, is AI a good fit for this general?

187
00:34:13.760 --> 00:34:32.750
John Ellis: So the first thing is to be careful about your problem decomposition. So to know exactly what the task is. And this sounds really obvious, but to be honest about, like, how well you really decompose a problem into steps.

188
00:34:32.790 --> 00:34:35.860
John Ellis: If, for instance, you go…

189
00:34:35.940 --> 00:34:48.620
John Ellis: I know now exactly what it is that I need. I have all of the things I think I would need to do it, I can write exactly those steps in order, and the AI just has to do it for me, so that's probably a great fit right off the bat.

190
00:34:48.900 --> 00:34:58.720
John Ellis: I think a lot of things are going to live in the yellows on these slides, which is that it's a little bit of both. Maybe you have a general idea, but you need to iterate on. You know, maybe you're…

191
00:34:58.840 --> 00:35:11.319
John Ellis: putting up a website. I don't know, and like, it's self-explanatory whether a website looks good, but you're not gonna know. Like, you're not gonna be able to specify where a box should go, you know? Just, like, when you see it, you're gonna be like, can you move that over?

192
00:35:12.060 --> 00:35:19.909
John Ellis: that's probably fine. You might want to define some things further, or understand what things are going to be active iteration, but having in your mind, like.

193
00:35:20.060 --> 00:35:24.269
John Ellis: What has to be defined up front? What am I going to actively iterate on?

194
00:35:24.760 --> 00:35:30.359
John Ellis: That's all effort that it's going to take on your part, so just understanding up front what that process is going to look like.

195
00:35:30.560 --> 00:35:33.500
John Ellis: Sometimes you…

196
00:35:33.640 --> 00:35:41.160
John Ellis: are really in this last case very firmly, where, you're kind of just, like, gonna see. Maybe, like.

197
00:35:41.360 --> 00:35:49.900
John Ellis: You're doing some exploratory data analysis, and you have no idea what

198
00:35:49.960 --> 00:36:04.570
John Ellis: you'd actually care about, you don't know the first thing about how the data is organized, like, I don't know, somehow you don't know what you're working with. Probably it's not going to be helpful to just throw AI at a task where you can't even ask what you want out specifically of it.

199
00:36:04.570 --> 00:36:13.950
John Ellis: So you have to be able to, like, be asking for something. What is it that you want to get out? At least as a starting point that you can iterate off of before you go.

200
00:36:16.960 --> 00:36:36.570
John Ellis: A second question to ask is always, what is the baseline? What does good look like? How will I know that a task is complete? And try to figure out what this would look like if, theoretically, there was no AI. So, if I had to go do this task myself, what would I expect to get as an output?

201
00:36:37.780 --> 00:36:46.890
John Ellis: Maybe you find yourself in the green. I know exactly when something is of good quality, I know how long it would take for me to do it right now.

202
00:36:47.750 --> 00:36:52.210
John Ellis: I'm not gonna, like, run into this rabbit hole with AI, then that's great.

203
00:36:53.830 --> 00:37:12.440
John Ellis: A lot of times, again, you'll find yourself in the middle, which maybe I've never done this specific task, but I do understand the domain. Maybe, like, you know, you've never written a code exactly like this, or read research papers on this very specific topic, but you do have a framework for understanding

204
00:37:12.620 --> 00:37:28.709
John Ellis: what you're going into, and you would know if things were going well, if you were getting the information you needed, what questions you want to ask, all that good stuff. Sometimes you might be in the… I don't really have a reference point for what it looks like. If you are just

205
00:37:28.990 --> 00:37:46.160
John Ellis: yeah, asking… sorry, all my exams are coding, it's really the only thing I do. If you're asking it to, generate, like, a webpage for you, or, like, a little app, because you want to, you know, mess around with some visualizations, but you have no idea,

206
00:37:46.160 --> 00:37:57.629
John Ellis: If those visualizations are helpful, or if the webpage is written well, or if it's stealing people's data or something, probably not a good fit for you at this time.

207
00:38:00.240 --> 00:38:05.840
John Ellis: The other critical question is, of course, what is your error tolerance? So…

208
00:38:05.910 --> 00:38:22.030
John Ellis: This goes back to some of our pitfalls. It's always important to define how bad would errors be if they were in there, and how easily do I think I could catch errors? If you think they'll be super obvious when things are going wrong, so our…

209
00:38:22.470 --> 00:38:27.640
John Ellis: dialogic reading, problem set that I mentioned was kind of a great

210
00:38:27.810 --> 00:38:34.030
John Ellis: Example of this, we had experts working on the project, and when they read a question, they just, like.

211
00:38:34.290 --> 00:38:51.239
John Ellis: thumbs up or thumbs down it immediately, right? They go like, yeah, that's good, or like, no, that's weird. It's very obvious when questions are good and bad. We have reviewers who are willing to evaluate them. And, AI is well guardrailed. It's not like our bad questions were to, like, talk hard.

212
00:38:51.250 --> 00:38:57.890
John Ellis: They were just gonna be, like, a little bit weird, and a 3-year-old might not have the wrong answer, and that was probably okay.

213
00:38:57.930 --> 00:39:02.390
John Ellis: So that was kind of a clear green light scenario where things were well defined.

214
00:39:02.950 --> 00:39:05.870
John Ellis: A yellow situation might look like

215
00:39:06.100 --> 00:39:13.199
John Ellis: some of your errors are acceptable, but if they really became systematic, it'd be a big problem. Or maybe, you really don't…

216
00:39:13.750 --> 00:39:16.800
John Ellis: You… some areas would be acceptable because

217
00:39:16.940 --> 00:39:33.999
John Ellis: nothing bad is gonna happen. Maybe the Jesse Golder situation is a great case, where if everybody gets an email to go talk to Jesse Golder, the worst thing is that he's gonna have a few too many conversations. And maybe the harm is relatively low, Jesse.

218
00:39:35.920 --> 00:39:46.440
John Ellis: But of course, there can be cases where an error is catastrophic, and maybe you wouldn't know that a catastrophic error happened, and if it did, it would mess everything up. Big repercussions.

219
00:39:46.750 --> 00:39:52.949
John Ellis: Either evaluate extremely rigorously and define that ahead of time, or don't proceed.

220
00:39:55.960 --> 00:40:01.730
John Ellis: Which then goes into number 4, which is how well can you evaluate?

221
00:40:01.900 --> 00:40:13.680
John Ellis: A tolerance for an error is one thing, but catching them can be an entirely different problem. So, this relates to question three, which is, let's say there are errors, and inevitably things will go wrong.

222
00:40:13.940 --> 00:40:19.029
John Ellis: How easily can I know? Do I have certain tests already that I know need to pass?

223
00:40:19.080 --> 00:40:35.689
John Ellis: could I write tests? It'll take me a while to formalize it, but, like, I do that, it's probably fine. Or if you just wouldn't know, then it's probably not good, because things will go wrong, and if you can't determine that, or define clearly what went wrong and where.

224
00:40:35.890 --> 00:40:37.670
John Ellis: You're getting yourself into a bad situation.

225
00:40:40.210 --> 00:40:46.540
John Ellis: Okay, and then question 5, it's really related, back to that first,

226
00:40:46.850 --> 00:41:05.479
John Ellis: terrible problem, terrible pressure point that plagues me, which is, what are the hidden decisions? As best as you can, I think it's good to keep in mind that the hidden decisions will happen, and to try to formulate what those could possibly be, and how bad they would be.

227
00:41:05.570 --> 00:41:24.939
John Ellis: Hopefully, you're in a position where you can anticipate what major choices will need to be made, or you could evaluate if unanticipated major choices were made. Sometimes, it feels really hard to anticipate what choices will be made, but you would still be able to know

228
00:41:25.010 --> 00:41:36.170
John Ellis: that some bad decision was made, and that's probably also okay. But the situation you don't want to be in is that you're not really sure what AI could assume about the problem.

229
00:41:36.290 --> 00:41:49.079
John Ellis: Probably because you can't specify it 100%, but also you wouldn't know how to know if something went wrong. Probably also because your evaluation is not as rigorous as it needs to be. And so if those things are sort of

230
00:41:50.020 --> 00:42:03.749
John Ellis: feeding on each other into this, like, well, I just won't know if it does something, then that's not good. And I sort of suggest here that probably go back to question one and reformulate what you're trying to do, because

231
00:42:04.050 --> 00:42:10.889
John Ellis: It's probably just not a great task if those two things are sort of beating up on each other, and you can't define them well enough.

232
00:42:11.330 --> 00:42:12.940
John Ellis: To not answer this question.

233
00:42:15.460 --> 00:42:30.370
John Ellis: So, question 6 is really an aggregate of the first 5, which I think is really a framework of, like, a go or do not go, based on how you've answered. And that is getting back to what is the real cost. So.

234
00:42:30.370 --> 00:42:36.939
John Ellis: If you've gone through the evaluation framework and you've decided that, for the most part, AI seems like a great fit, then that's awesome.

235
00:42:38.050 --> 00:42:53.730
John Ellis: Sometimes, you'll be in a situation where, you know, a lot of those yellow flag situations were, okay, well, you're gonna have to spend some time evaluating rigorously. Okay, you're gonna have to spend some time writing really detailed specs. Okay, you're gonna have to spend some time iterating.

236
00:42:54.450 --> 00:42:59.539
John Ellis: at some point, maybe that cost isn't worth it anymore, right? You're gonna spend so much time

237
00:42:59.720 --> 00:43:04.110
John Ellis: writing all of these evaluations and checks and stuff, you could have just done it.

238
00:43:04.370 --> 00:43:06.890
John Ellis: And sometimes that'll be the case.

239
00:43:07.020 --> 00:43:17.089
John Ellis: probably if you had multiple of those red flags, like, there would be a ton of formulation work that has to happen, and so it's just not a great fit for AI at this point.

240
00:43:19.970 --> 00:43:20.830
John Ellis: Okay.

241
00:43:21.360 --> 00:43:39.460
John Ellis: So it might sound like what I'm saying based on all of that, is that if you got green flags, then you're good to use AI. If you got red or yellow flags, then you're not allowed to use AI. Do not go, no AI for you. And that is not what I'm saying. I want to be clear. I think that

242
00:43:39.730 --> 00:43:45.420
John Ellis: The key is that if a portion of your project isn't a good fit, or the whole project.

243
00:43:46.150 --> 00:43:53.939
John Ellis: As one gigantic chunk isn't a good fit, you always have the option to decompose it into smaller parts.

244
00:43:54.090 --> 00:44:12.769
John Ellis: rerun this framework on some smaller part, and I'm sure you can find a part that is small enough that AI can help you with it. Like, seriously, even if 100% of your data pipeline you can't do, except that AI can write a Python script to, like, resize your images, like, that's saving you time.

245
00:44:13.090 --> 00:44:20.109
John Ellis: So, there's probably some little component that is well-specified enough that AI is going to help accelerate you.

246
00:44:20.360 --> 00:44:25.249
John Ellis: And I think it's just about finding what that piece is for your specific use case.

247
00:44:26.130 --> 00:44:38.050
John Ellis: So really that is the true question 7 that I think is important, is really asking yourself, what is a piece that I'm confident AI can help with?

248
00:44:38.100 --> 00:44:57.639
John Ellis: And earlier in this talk, I gave you this analogy of bridges and an ocean, but enough bridges will cross an ocean. So if you just find out what your bridges are, and you take those little steps one at a time, you will build out a full project that maybe feels really out of your scope, if you're able to just specify the steps.

249
00:45:00.070 --> 00:45:03.669
John Ellis: Okay so my final thoughts are largely…

250
00:45:04.020 --> 00:45:21.349
John Ellis: a wrap-up. But just these slides will be in the GitHub, so just as a quick reference guide if you want to reference a few things of exactly what I said. There's a few cases, I think, that are very obvious about when AI tends to disappoint or work well.

251
00:45:21.390 --> 00:45:33.990
John Ellis: that tends to disappoint is believing you have failure across the board in that evaluation framework. Basically, it's just hard to know what the task is that you want to happen. And when AI tends to work well, I think are very obvious cases.

252
00:45:33.990 --> 00:45:43.490
John Ellis: where you're just wanting to, like, do something over and over again, or it's, like, super low stakes, and, you know, you're just chatting with AI, right? Like, that's the extremely low stakes.

253
00:45:43.490 --> 00:45:52.059
John Ellis: version where, like, who cares if it tells you something wrong or whatever? I mean, you know, you should use your brain to know that, but…

254
00:45:52.090 --> 00:45:54.930
John Ellis: it's not gonna be the end of the world.

255
00:45:55.240 --> 00:46:06.010
John Ellis: So there's lots of cases that I think feel very obvious, like, oh, I'll know exactly if this did what it was supposed to be. All my images will now be size 512, like, that's how I'll know it did what it was supposed to be. That's a great case.

256
00:46:06.280 --> 00:46:15.179
John Ellis: The reality, of course, is that lots of things live in the middle ground, where AI can work, but maybe it'll take a lot of effort, expertise.

257
00:46:15.560 --> 00:46:27.389
John Ellis: human evaluation, iteration, you'll have to write some skills, you'll have to verify lots of things. And the question really to ask isn't necessarily if AI can do this, because

258
00:46:27.400 --> 00:46:37.250
John Ellis: as we've seen, and as you probably know, if you throw something at AI, it will do it, whether it's going to do it well or not. So the question is really to ask, is it going to do it well?

259
00:46:37.370 --> 00:46:42.470
John Ellis: at the level I want it to, and actually save me time, what it takes to get to that level.

260
00:46:43.250 --> 00:46:46.040
John Ellis: And what is the piece where that does speak to you?

261
00:46:48.160 --> 00:46:51.689
John Ellis: I think if there's any one sort of…

262
00:46:51.770 --> 00:47:02.920
John Ellis: key takeaway. It's that this idea of evaluation and validation is really the name of the game. It's really hard, I think, to have, like, perfect

263
00:47:02.930 --> 00:47:22.210
John Ellis: trust in AI once you start to see times that it's failed you. But the idea is not to have perfect trust that it's going to do everything right 100% of the time. The idea is for you to be able to understand when it hasn't done right, and just be able to correct it. And so going into every

264
00:47:22.440 --> 00:47:37.850
John Ellis: time that you're using AI for a significant piece, with an idea of the metrics and the scope and the baselines, and what you're going to check to make sure it's all proceeding how it's supposed to, is really the most helpful thing to make sure that things aren't derailing and getting into a space

